\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
      s"Welcome back,
 Commander ${user.name}"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
    else
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
      s"Hello,
 ${user.name}"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Immutability by Default
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Renaissance approach,
 we favor 
\family typewriter
val
\family default
 over 
\family typewriter
var
\family default
.
 By making data immutable,
 we eliminate a whole category of "spooky action at a distance" bugs.
 When you want to change data,
 you don't mutate it;
 you transform it into a new version.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Expressions,
 Not Statements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In many languages,
 an 
\family typewriter
if
\family default
 block or a 
\family typewriter
try
\family default
 block is a "statement" that does something.
 In Scala,
 almost everything is an 
\series bold
expression
\series default
 that returns a value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// The result of the 'if' is assigned directly to the variable
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val status = if temperature > 30 then "Hot" else "Comfortable"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Scalable Language
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The name "Scala" comes from 
\emph on
SCAlable LAnguage
\emph default
.
 This refers to the language's ability to create small,
 "internal" Domain Specific Languages (DSLs).
 This is why libraries like 
\family typewriter
sttp
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
Doobie
\family default
 feel like they are part of the language itself rather than external additions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Unified Type System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike Java,
 which has "primitive" types (like 
\family typewriter
int
\family default
) and "objects" (like 
\family typewriter
Integer
\family default
),
 Scala treats everything as an object.
 However,
 the compiler is smart enough to optimize these down to primitives under the hood to ensure there is no performance penalty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Scala Crystallized—
A Language at a Glance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter serves as a formal map of the Scala language.
 It covers the structure of source files,
 the type system hierarchy,
 the nature of expressions,
 and the mechanics of error handling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
1.
 Source and Program Layout
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scala source files typically end in .
\family typewriter
scala
\family default
.
 Unlike Java,
 the file name does not have to match the class name,
 and multiple classes,
 traits,
 and objects can reside in a single file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Packages
\series default
:
 Defined at the top of the file.
 Scala supports "scoped" packages:
 
\family typewriter
package com.project.core
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Imports
\series default
:
 Can occur anywhere (top of file,
 inside a class,
 or inside a method).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\family typewriter
import scala.collection.mutable._
\family default
 (Wildcard)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\family typewriter
import java.util.{List,
 Map}
\family default
 (Selective)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\family typewriter
import java.sql.{Date => SqlDate}
\family default
 (Renaming)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The Entry Point
\series default
:
 A program starts in an 
\family typewriter
object 
\family default
(a singleton) with a 
\family typewriter
main
\family default
 method or by extending 
\family typewriter
App
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Anatomy of a Scala Source File
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Header:
 Packages and Imports
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Unlike Java,
 Scala allows "chained" package declarations and imports that can be scoped to specific blocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Package Declaration
\series default
:
 Defines the logical namespace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Imports
\series default
:
 These are not restricted to the top of the file,
 but standard practice places them here.
 Scala supports renaming and hiding members during import to avoid name collisions (common when mixing Java and Scala libraries).
\end_layout

