\begin_layout Enumerate
The Main Body:
 Traits,
 Classes,
 and Objects 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
A single file often contains three distinct but related components.
 This is a departure from Java’s "one-file-one-public-class" rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Interface (The Trait)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We define the "what" before the "how." In a library context,
 this is often a trait that defines the contract.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The Implementation (The Class)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The concrete logic.
 Scala classes typically use 
\series bold
Constructor Parameters 
\series default
instead of field declarations with setters.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The Companion Object
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
This is where "static" logic lives.
 It shares the same name as the class.
 It is the idiomatic home for:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Factory methods (
\family typewriter
apply
\family default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Data mappers (e.g.,
 mapping a Doobie 
\family typewriter
Row
\family default
 to a 
\family typewriter
User 
\family default
class).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Constants specific to that type.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
